{"title_page": "Princess Nokia", "text_new": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Princess Nokia\n| background       = solo_singer\n| caption          = Princess Nokia- Shot in New York\n| birth_name       = Destiny Nicole Frasqueri\n| alias            = {{hlist|Wavy Spice|Destiny Nicole Ortiz|Destiny}}\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1992|6|14}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]],  U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[emo rap]]<ref>http://musicandriots.com/princess-nokia-reigns-supreme-as-the-queen-of-emo-rap-at-special-house-of-vans-chicago-2/</ref>|[[electro hop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|[[Rapping|Rapper]]|[[Singing|singer]]|[[songwriter]]}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|princessnokia.org}}\n| image            = \n}}\n'''Destiny Nicole Frasqueri''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/7bdeme/stream-destinys-honeysuckle-the-funky-follow-up-to-princess-nokias-metallic-butterfly-456|title=Stream Destiny's 'Honeysuckle,' the Funky Follow-Up to 'Metallic Butterfly'|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|first=Wilbert L.|last=Cooper|date=September 21, 2015|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> (born June 14, 1992),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/thefader/videos/10154716981891903/|title=Happy birthday Princess Nokia |work=[[The FADER]]|date=June 14, 2017|accessdate= April 14, 2018}}</ref> better known by their [[stage name]] '''Princess Nokia''', are American rappers and actresses of [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/12/princess-nokia-talks-santeria/|title=Princess Nokia Talks Infusing Santer\u00eda In Her Music|work=Vibe|first=Shanice|last=Davis|date=2016-12-14}}</ref> Princess Nokia released their debut album Metallic Butterfy in 2014, followed by the 2015 mixtape, ''Honeysuckle'' (as Destiny). Frasqueri, as Princess Nokia, then released the ''1992'' EP, followed by their debut album, ''[[1992 Deluxe]]'', which served as their breakthrough album. In 2018, they released the emo-rap mixtape, ''A Girl Cried Red'', before releasing two albums in 2020, ''Everything Sucks'' and ''[[Everything Is Beautiful (Princess Nokia album)|Everything Is Beautiful]]''. Princess Nokia has also hosted an Apple Music radio show and acted in the independent film, ''Angelfish''.\n\n== Early life ==\nAt the age of 10, Frasqueri lost their mother to [[AIDS]].<ref name=vogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/afropunk-festival-2017-princess-nokia|title=This Time, Princess Nokia Is Going to Do It Right|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|first=Jenna|last=Marotta|date=August 28, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> Between the ages of 9 and 16, they were in foster care. During their time in foster care, their foster mother was physically abusive.<ref name=\"vogue\" /> After they left foster care, they went to live with their grandmother.<ref>{{Citation|last=Snobette|title=Princess Nokia: \"There's No Money in Record Deals & I'm Not Looking to Be Taken Advantage of\"|date=2016-07-05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oWitkBM6gOo&t=571s|accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref><ref name=vogue/> At the age of sixteen, Frasqueri started writing rhymes.<ref name=paper/> They lived around [[East Harlem]] and the [[Lower East Side]] of [[New York City]] at the time.<ref name=\"paper\">{{cite news|title=Wavy Spice is Making \"High-Tech airy Girl Music\"...and we're Listening|url=http://www.papermag.com/2013/10/wavy_spice.php|accessdate=5 December 2014|work=Paper|date=14 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Princess Nokia.jpg|thumb|Princess Nokia performing in 2014]]\n\n=== Early career and ''Metallic Butterfly'' (2010-2016) ===\nFrasqueri recorded their first song, \"Destiny\", in 2010, and released it under the name \"Wavy Spice\" on their [[SoundCloud]] page and their YouTube channel in mid-2012. It was largely autobiographical and gained modest popularity. Subsequently, they released their second track, \"Bitch I'm Posh\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /><ref>[http://noisey.vice.com/ja/blog/wavy-spice-bitch-im-posh Wavy Spice\" \"Bitch I'm Posh\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220182519/http://noisey.vice.com/ja/blog/wavy-spice-bitch-im-posh |date=2014-02-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"paper\" /> The track went viral, and as of March 2020, received 170,000 plays on SoundCloud.<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jan/16/wavy-spice Wavy Spice (New band of the day No 1,679)]\" [[The Guardian]]. Accessed 27 November 2016</ref> Frasqueri then released ''YAYA (Yaya is a [[Ta\u00edno|Taino]] word)''<ref>{{Citation|last=Princess Nokia|title=Wavy Spice - YAYA|date=2012-10-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=90Y9BdyZcQc|accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> as a commentary of perceptions of colonial history.<ref name=\"Remezcla\">{{Cite news|url=http://remezcla.com/features/music/princess-nokia-new-age-hood-leader/|title=Princess Nokia is Our New Age Hood Leader|work=Remezcla|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\nFrasqueri continued to release singles, such as ''Dragons'', a ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' inspired piece, ''Honeysuckle'', and ''Vicki Gotti'' until changing their moniker to Princess Nokia. They released their mixtape, ''1992'', on Soundcloud and began touring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/princessnokiaofficial/sets/1992-deluxe|title=1992 Deluxe|website=SoundCloud|language=en|access-date=2018-01-06}}</ref>\n\nFrasqueri claims Princess Nokia is an [[alter ego]],<ref>[http://bullettmedia.com/article/wavy-spice-harlem-is-burning/ Wavy Spice: Harlem Is Burning]</ref> which they introduced with the track \"Nokia\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">[http://bullettmedia.com/article/hear-wavy-spice-transform-into-princess-nokia-on-nokia/ Track Premiere: Hear Wavy Spice Transform Into Princess Nokia on 'Nokia'<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> They released an album named ''Metallic Butterfly'' on May 12, 2014, and was debuted on ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' and Soundcloud.<ref>{{cite news|title=Princess Nokia's 'Metallic Butterfly'|url=https://www.vice.com/read/princess-nokias-metallic-butterfly|accessdate=5 December 2014|work=Vice|date=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== ''1992 Deluxe'' (2017-2018) ===\nIn February 2017, Frasqueri confronted a member of the audience at a charity concert at [[Cambridge University]] whom they accused of \"mouthing dirty obscenities like 'show me your tits'.\" The alleged harasser denied yelling such obscenities and told ''[[The Cambridge Student]]'': \"I was standing in the audience and was told by a fellow audience member that the name of the performer was 'Abigail'. Given that I was enjoying the performance, I shouted out 'Let's go Abigail!'. After I shouted this, they came down from the stage. They slapped me and threw drinks on me.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.out.com/music/2017/2/22/rapper-princess-nokia-punches-audience-member-after-being-harassed-stage|title=Rapper Princess Nokia Punches Audience Member After Being Harassed On Stage|date=22 February 2017|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tcs.cam.ac.uk/news/0036769-fashion-show-headliner-ends-set-early-after-hitting-audience-member.html|title=Fashion show headliner ends set early after hitting audience member|date=15 February 2017|work=[[The Cambridge Student]]|accessdate=23 February 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224061717/http://www.tcs.cam.ac.uk/news/0036769-fashion-show-headliner-ends-set-early-after-hitting-audience-member.html|archive-date=24 February 2017}}</ref> After returning to the stage, Nokia told the crowd \"that's what you do when a White boy disrespects you\".<ref>https://heatst.com/culture-wars/rapper-princess-nokia-assaults-white-boy-in-audience-who-called-her-abigail/</ref>\n\nOn September 8, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/08/princess-nokia-1992-deluxe-mixtape-release-date/|title=Princess Nokia Shares '1992 Deluxe' Album Release Date|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|first=Peter A.|last=Berry|date=August 28, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> they released their debut studio album, ''[[1992 Deluxe]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/09/08/princess-nokia-1992-deluxe|title=Listen To Princess Nokia's New Project 1992 Deluxe|work=[[The Fader]]|first=Jordan|last=Darville|date=September 8, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018|quote=The New York rapper considers this new release to be her debut LP.}}</ref> which was an expanded version of their 2016 mixtape, ''1992''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/09/princess-nokia-releases-1992-deluxe-album-stream/|title=Princess Nokia releases 1992 Deluxe album: Stream|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|first=Michelle|last=Geslani|date=September 9, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> It peaked at #25 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Heatseekers Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/princess-nokia/chart-history/heatseekers-albums|title=Princess Nokia - Heatseekers Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' listed it as the 32nd best album of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/nmes-albums-of-the-year-2017-2161481|title=NME's Albums of The Year 2017|work=[[NME]]|date=December 27, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Frasqueri made headlines again when a viral video surfaced of them throwing hot soup in a man's face whilst on a subway journey to [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://bust.com/feminism/193616-princess-nokia-armed-with-a-fist-full-of-soup-fights-off-a-subway-racist.html|title=Princess Nokia, Armed With Soup, Fights Off a Subway Racist|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-gb}}</ref> The rapper heard a white man shouting racial slurs at a group of teenagers, and decided to take action against the racist remarks by slapping the man and throwing their hot soup on him.<ref name=\":0\" /> They took to [[Twitter]] saying: \"this bigot called this group of teenage boys 'n****s' on the train so I stood up and slapped him and everybody on the train backed me up\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== ''A Girl Cried Red'' (2018-2019) ===\nNokia also has debuted a new radio show on Apple's Beats 1 Radio on February 18, 2018. Episodes will air every other Sunday and allow listeners to get acquainted with the inner workings of Nokia's mind. They have a total of 6 episodes labelled: \"The Voices in My Head with Princess Nokia.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/entry/princess_nokia_debuts_voices_in_my_head|title=Princess Nokia Debuts Voices in My Head|website=altpress.com|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Nokia was chosen as one of the six ambassadors by [[Maison Margiela]] to promote their new fragrance, Mutiny.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/meet-maison-margielas-new-fragrance-mutiny|title=Meet Maison Margiela's New Fragrance Mutiny|publisher=Vogue|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Nokia re-released the album ''Metallic Butterfly'' under the label Rough Trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://audiodorks.com/music/1445516354/metallic-butterfly-princess-nokia|title=Metallic Butterfly|publisher=Rough Trade|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019 they had their debut performance as an actor in the indie movie ''\u201cAngelfish\"''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/angelfish/|title=Angelfish by Brian Shaer|work=Film Threat|access-date=2020-01-14|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://remezcla.com/features/film/angelfish-review-peter-andrew-lee-princess-nokia/|title=Angelfish: Film Review|work=Remezcla|access-date=2020-02-21|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Everything Sucks'' and ''Everything is Beautiful'' (2020 - present) ===\nIn February 2020, Nokia released two albums: ''Everything Sucks'' and ''[[Everything is Beautiful (Princess Nokia album)|Everything is Beautiful]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/princess-nokia-everything-is-beautiful-everything-sucks-review-a4374241.html|title=Princess Nokia's Everything Is Beautiful/Everything Sucks is audacious|date=2020-02-28|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThey are a strong supporter of intersectional [[feminism]], founding the ''Smart Girl Club'' with Milah Libin, a podcast where they discuss healthy living and urban feminism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/sep/08/princess-nokia-destiny-frasqueri-rap-riot-grrrl|title=Princess Nokia: 'At my shows, girls can take up space the way men do'|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=8 September 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/princess-nokia/|title=Princess Nokia, an Artist Making a Career All Her Own|last=Mallett|first=Whitney|date=2016-08-26|website=V Magazine|access-date=2018-01-05}}</ref><ref>https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/ypnpzk/why-princess-nokia-matters-now-more-than-ever</ref><ref>https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/9kb53p/smart-girl-club-meet-princess-nokia-and-two-of-the-most-important-women-in-her-life</ref> The rapper is an active practictioner of [[Santer\u00eda]], and has shared their own experience with clairvoyance and spirituality that they infuse their music with.\n\nFrasqueri identifies as [[bisexuality|bisexual]] and has stated such in a past interview, they have also talked about how growing up near the [[queer]] community of New York City was an important part of their life. The early stages of their musical career began through performing at gay clubs, and they gained popularity among the gay nightlife scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/music/2017/10/02/how-princess-nokia-achieved-gay-new-york-dream|title=How Princess Nokia Achieved the 'Gay New York Dream'|last=Moran|first=Justin|date=10 October 2017|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thelgbtsentinel.com/bi-artist-spotlight-radical-self-love-princess-nokia/|title=Bi Artist Spotlight: Radical Self Love with Princess Nokia|date=9 May 2017|work=The LGBT Sentinel|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hill |first1=Zahara |title=rincess Nokia On Being Sexually Fluid And Making Music For Girls With The 'Delusional Confidence Of Barbra Streisand' |url=https://blavity.com/princess-nokia-on-being-sexually-fluid-and-making-music-for-girls-with-the-delusional-confidence-of-barbra-streisand?category1=music&subCat=culture |website=Blavity |date=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrasqueri also opened up about their identity as a [[Gender variance|gender non-conforming]] person and uses both they/them as well as she/her pronouns.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanders |first1=Wren |title=Out Loud: Princess Nokia Is Done Explaining Themself |url=https://www.them.us/story/princess-nokia-interview-everything-sucks-everything-is-beautiful |website=Them |date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stone |first1=Avery |title=King Princess Is Making Queer Pop Anthems for the Next Generation |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/8xwedz/king-princess-cheap-queen-interview-profile-v26n4 |website=Vice |date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ushe |first1=Naledi |title=Princess Nokia Opens Up About Being a Gender Non-Conforming Artist in 'Playboy' Equality Issue |url=https://okmagazine.com/photos/princess-nokia-gender-non-conforming-artist-playboy-equality/ |website=OK Magazine |date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Studio albums ===\n*''Metallic Butterfly'' (2014, in 2018 was released a deluxe edition)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8490309/princess-nokia-metallic-butterfly-reissue|title=Princess Nokia Re-Issues 'Metallic Butterfly'|date=2018-12-14|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*''[[1992 Deluxe]]'' (2017, as a deluxe edition of their EP of the same title)\n*''Everything Sucks'' (2020)\n*''[[Everything is Beautiful (Princess Nokia album)|Everything is Beautiful]]'' (2020)\n\n=== EP ===\n\n* ''1992'' (2016)\n* ''G.O.A.T.'' (2017)\n\n=== Mixtapes ===\n\n* ''Honeysuckle'' (2015, as Destiny)\n*''A Girl Cried Red'' (2018)\n\n=== Guest appearances ===\n* [[Ratking (group)|Ratking]] \u2013 \"Puerto Rican Judo\" from ''[[So It Goes (Ratking album)|So It Goes]]'' (2014)\n* [[Mykki Blanco]] \u2013 \"Wish You Would\" from ''Spring/Summer 2014'' (2014)\n* Ratking \u2013 \"Steep Tech\" from ''[[700-Fill]]'' (2015)\n* [[K. Michelle]] \u2013 \"Outro\" from ''[[Kimberly: The People I Used to Know]]'' (2017)\n* [[Show Me the Body]] \u2013 \"Spit\" from ''Corpus I'' (2017)\n* Josh Forehead \u2013 \"Fanta\" from ''Summer 2014'' (2017)\n* [[Silverstein (band)|Silverstein]] - \"Madness\" from ''[[A Beautiful Place to Drown]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===Sweden GAFFA Awards===\nDelivered since 2010, the GAFFA Awards (Swedish: GAFFA Priset) are a Swedish award that rewards popular music awarded by the magazine of the same name.\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| Themself\n| Best Foreign New Act\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://gaffa.se/nyhet/124897/gaffa-priset-2018-och-de-nominerade-aer/|title=GAFFA-Priset 2018 \u2013 och de nominerade \u00e4r ...|work=GAFFA|access-date=September 3, 2019 |location=Sweden|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* [[List of self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers]]\n* [[Nuyorican]]\n* [[Puerto Ricans in New York City]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube | u = dnfrasqueri }}\n* [http://princessnokia.org/ Princess Nokia's official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bisexual feminists]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:Trip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Indie rappers]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:LGBT rappers]]\n[[Category:People of Afro-Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n[[Category:People from the Lower East Side]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Princess Nokia\n| background       = solo_singer\n| caption          = Princess Nokia- Shot in New York\n| birth_name       = Destiny Nicole Frasqueri\n| alias            = {{hlist|Wavy Spice|Destiny Nicole Ortiz|Destiny}}\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1992|6|14}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]],  U.S.\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[emo rap]]<ref>http://musicandriots.com/princess-nokia-reigns-supreme-as-the-queen-of-emo-rap-at-special-house-of-vans-chicago-2/</ref>|[[electro hop]]}}\n| occupation       = {{hlist|[[Rapping|Rapper]]|[[Singing|singer]]|[[songwriter]]}}\n| years_active     = 2010\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|princessnokia.org}}\n| image            = \n}}\n'''Destiny Nicole Frasqueri''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/7bdeme/stream-destinys-honeysuckle-the-funky-follow-up-to-princess-nokias-metallic-butterfly-456|title=Stream Destiny's 'Honeysuckle,' the Funky Follow-Up to 'Metallic Butterfly'|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|first=Wilbert L.|last=Cooper|date=September 21, 2015|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> (born June 14, 1992),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/thefader/videos/10154716981891903/|title=Happy birthday Princess Nokia |work=[[The FADER]]|date=June 14, 2017|accessdate= April 14, 2018}}</ref> better known by their [[stage name]] '''Princess Nokia''', is an American rapper and actress of [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vibe.com/2016/12/princess-nokia-talks-santeria/|title=Princess Nokia Talks Infusing Santer\u00eda In Her Music|work=Vibe|first=Shanice|last=Davis|date=2016-12-14}}</ref> Princess Nokia released their debut album Metallic Butterfy in 2014, followed by the 2015 mixtape, ''Honeysuckle'' (as Destiny). Frasqueri, as Princess Nokia, then released the ''1992'' EP, followed by their debut album, ''[[1992 Deluxe]]'', which served as their breakthrough album. In 2018, they released the emo-rap mixtape, ''A Girl Cried Red'', before releasing two albums in 2020, ''Everything Sucks'' and ''[[Everything Is Beautiful (Princess Nokia album)|Everything Is Beautiful]]''. Princess Nokia has also hosted an Apple Music radio show and acted in the independent film, ''Angelfish''.\n\n== Early life ==\nAt the age of 10, Frasqueri lost their mother to [[AIDS]].<ref name=vogue>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/afropunk-festival-2017-princess-nokia|title=This Time, Princess Nokia Is Going to Do It Right|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|first=Jenna|last=Marotta|date=August 28, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> Between the ages of 9 and 16, they were in foster care. During their time in foster care, their foster mother was physically abusive.<ref name=\"vogue\" /> After they left foster care, they went to live with their grandmother.<ref>{{Citation|last=Snobette|title=Princess Nokia: \"There's No Money in Record Deals & I'm Not Looking to Be Taken Advantage of\"|date=2016-07-05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oWitkBM6gOo&t=571s|accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref><ref name=vogue/> At the age of sixteen, Frasqueri started writing rhymes.<ref name=paper/> They lived around [[East Harlem]] and the [[Lower East Side]] of [[New York City]] at the time.<ref name=\"paper\">{{cite news|title=Wavy Spice is Making \"High-Tech airy Girl Music\"...and we're Listening|url=http://www.papermag.com/2013/10/wavy_spice.php|accessdate=5 December 2014|work=Paper|date=14 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Princess Nokia.jpg|thumb|Princess Nokia performing in 2014]]\n\n=== Early career and ''Metallic Butterfly'' (2010-2016) ===\nFrasqueri recorded their first song, \"Destiny\", in 2010, and released it under the name \"Wavy Spice\" on their [[SoundCloud]] page and their YouTube channel in mid-2012. It was largely autobiographical and gained modest popularity. Subsequently, they released their second track, \"Bitch I'm Posh\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" /><ref>[http://noisey.vice.com/ja/blog/wavy-spice-bitch-im-posh Wavy Spice\" \"Bitch I'm Posh\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220182519/http://noisey.vice.com/ja/blog/wavy-spice-bitch-im-posh |date=2014-02-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"paper\" /> The track went viral, and as of March 2020, received 170,000 plays on SoundCloud.<ref>\"[https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jan/16/wavy-spice Wavy Spice (New band of the day No 1,679)]\" [[The Guardian]]. Accessed 27 November 2016</ref> Frasqueri then released ''YAYA (Yaya is a [[Ta\u00edno|Taino]] word)''<ref>{{Citation|last=Princess Nokia|title=Wavy Spice - YAYA|date=2012-10-29|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=90Y9BdyZcQc|accessdate=2018-05-10}}</ref> as a commentary of perceptions of colonial history.<ref name=\"Remezcla\">{{Cite news|url=http://remezcla.com/features/music/princess-nokia-new-age-hood-leader/|title=Princess Nokia is Our New Age Hood Leader|work=Remezcla|access-date=2017-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\nFrasqueri continued to release singles, such as ''Dragons'', a ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' inspired piece, ''Honeysuckle'', and ''Vicki Gotti'' until changing their moniker to Princess Nokia. They released their mixtape, ''1992'', on Soundcloud and began touring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://soundcloud.com/princessnokiaofficial/sets/1992-deluxe|title=1992 Deluxe|website=SoundCloud|language=en|access-date=2018-01-06}}</ref>\n\nFrasqueri claims Princess Nokia is an [[alter ego]],<ref>[http://bullettmedia.com/article/wavy-spice-harlem-is-burning/ Wavy Spice: Harlem Is Burning]</ref> which they introduced with the track \"Nokia\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">[http://bullettmedia.com/article/hear-wavy-spice-transform-into-princess-nokia-on-nokia/ Track Premiere: Hear Wavy Spice Transform Into Princess Nokia on 'Nokia'<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> They released an album named ''Metallic Butterfly'' on May 12, 2014, and was debuted on ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' and Soundcloud.<ref>{{cite news|title=Princess Nokia's 'Metallic Butterfly'|url=https://www.vice.com/read/princess-nokias-metallic-butterfly|accessdate=5 December 2014|work=Vice|date=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== ''1992 Deluxe'' (2017-2018) ===\nIn February 2017, Frasqueri confronted a member of the audience at a charity concert at [[Cambridge University]] whom they accused of \"mouthing dirty obscenities like 'show me your tits'.\" The alleged harasser denied yelling such obscenities and told ''[[The Cambridge Student]]'': \"I was standing in the audience and was told by a fellow audience member that the name of the performer was 'Abigail'. Given that I was enjoying the performance, I shouted out 'Let's go Abigail!'. After I shouted this, they came down from the stage. They slapped me and threw drinks on me.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.out.com/music/2017/2/22/rapper-princess-nokia-punches-audience-member-after-being-harassed-stage|title=Rapper Princess Nokia Punches Audience Member After Being Harassed On Stage|date=22 February 2017|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tcs.cam.ac.uk/news/0036769-fashion-show-headliner-ends-set-early-after-hitting-audience-member.html|title=Fashion show headliner ends set early after hitting audience member|date=15 February 2017|work=[[The Cambridge Student]]|accessdate=23 February 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224061717/http://www.tcs.cam.ac.uk/news/0036769-fashion-show-headliner-ends-set-early-after-hitting-audience-member.html|archive-date=24 February 2017}}</ref> After returning to the stage, Nokia told the crowd \"that's what you do when a White boy disrespects you\".<ref>https://heatst.com/culture-wars/rapper-princess-nokia-assaults-white-boy-in-audience-who-called-her-abigail/</ref>\n\nOn September 8, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/08/princess-nokia-1992-deluxe-mixtape-release-date/|title=Princess Nokia Shares '1992 Deluxe' Album Release Date|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|first=Peter A.|last=Berry|date=August 28, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> they released their debut studio album, ''[[1992 Deluxe]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/2017/09/08/princess-nokia-1992-deluxe|title=Listen To Princess Nokia's New Project 1992 Deluxe|work=[[The Fader]]|first=Jordan|last=Darville|date=September 8, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018|quote=The New York rapper considers this new release to be her debut LP.}}</ref> which was an expanded version of their 2016 mixtape, ''1992''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2017/09/princess-nokia-releases-1992-deluxe-album-stream/|title=Princess Nokia releases 1992 Deluxe album: Stream|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|first=Michelle|last=Geslani|date=September 9, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> It peaked at #25 on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s [[Heatseekers Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/princess-nokia/chart-history/heatseekers-albums|title=Princess Nokia - Heatseekers Albums|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' listed it as the 32nd best album of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/nmes-albums-of-the-year-2017-2161481|title=NME's Albums of The Year 2017|work=[[NME]]|date=December 27, 2017|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017, Frasqueri made headlines again when a viral video surfaced of them throwing hot soup in a man's face whilst on a subway journey to [[Brooklyn]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://bust.com/feminism/193616-princess-nokia-armed-with-a-fist-full-of-soup-fights-off-a-subway-racist.html|title=Princess Nokia, Armed With Soup, Fights Off a Subway Racist|access-date=2018-03-07|language=en-gb}}</ref> The rapper heard a white man shouting racial slurs at a group of teenagers, and decided to take action against the racist remarks by slapping the man and throwing their hot soup on him.<ref name=\":0\" /> They took to [[Twitter]] saying: \"this bigot called this group of teenage boys 'n****s' on the train so I stood up and slapped him and everybody on the train backed me up\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== ''A Girl Cried Red'' (2018-2019) ===\nNokia also has debuted a new radio show on Apple's Beats 1 Radio on February 18, 2018. Episodes will air every other Sunday and allow listeners to get acquainted with the inner workings of Nokia's mind. They have a total of 6 episodes labelled: \"The Voices in My Head with Princess Nokia.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.altpress.com/news/entry/princess_nokia_debuts_voices_in_my_head|title=Princess Nokia Debuts Voices in My Head|website=altpress.com|access-date=2018-03-08}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, Nokia was chosen as one of the six ambassadors by [[Maison Margiela]] to promote their new fragrance, Mutiny.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.co.uk/article/meet-maison-margielas-new-fragrance-mutiny|title=Meet Maison Margiela's New Fragrance Mutiny|publisher=Vogue|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Nokia re-released the album ''Metallic Butterfly'' under the label Rough Trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://audiodorks.com/music/1445516354/metallic-butterfly-princess-nokia|title=Metallic Butterfly|publisher=Rough Trade|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019 they had their debut performance as an actor in the indie movie ''\u201cAngelfish\"''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://filmthreat.com/reviews/angelfish/|title=Angelfish by Brian Shaer|work=Film Threat|access-date=2020-01-14|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://remezcla.com/features/film/angelfish-review-peter-andrew-lee-princess-nokia/|title=Angelfish: Film Review|work=Remezcla|access-date=2020-02-21|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Everything Sucks'' and ''Everything is Beautiful'' (2020 - present) ===\nIn February 2020, Nokia released two albums: ''Everything Sucks'' and ''[[Everything is Beautiful (Princess Nokia album)|Everything is Beautiful]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/music/princess-nokia-everything-is-beautiful-everything-sucks-review-a4374241.html|title=Princess Nokia's Everything Is Beautiful/Everything Sucks is audacious|date=2020-02-28|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThey are a strong supporter of intersectional [[feminism]], founding the ''Smart Girl Club'' with Milah Libin, a podcast where they discuss healthy living and urban feminism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/sep/08/princess-nokia-destiny-frasqueri-rap-riot-grrrl|title=Princess Nokia: 'At my shows, girls can take up space the way men do'|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=8 September 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=5 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vmagazine.com/article/princess-nokia/|title=Princess Nokia, an Artist Making a Career All Her Own|last=Mallett|first=Whitney|date=2016-08-26|website=V Magazine|access-date=2018-01-05}}</ref><ref>https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/ypnpzk/why-princess-nokia-matters-now-more-than-ever</ref><ref>https://i-d.vice.com/en_us/article/9kb53p/smart-girl-club-meet-princess-nokia-and-two-of-the-most-important-women-in-her-life</ref> The rapper is an active practictioner of [[Santer\u00eda]], and has shared their own experience with clairvoyance and spirituality that they infuse their music with.\n\nFrasqueri identifies as [[bisexuality|bisexual]] and has stated such in a past interview, they have also talked about how growing up near the [[queer]] community of New York City was an important part of their life. The early stages of their musical career began through performing at gay clubs, and they gained popularity among the gay nightlife scene.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.out.com/music/2017/10/02/how-princess-nokia-achieved-gay-new-york-dream|title=How Princess Nokia Achieved the 'Gay New York Dream'|last=Moran|first=Justin|date=10 October 2017|work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]]|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thelgbtsentinel.com/bi-artist-spotlight-radical-self-love-princess-nokia/|title=Bi Artist Spotlight: Radical Self Love with Princess Nokia|date=9 May 2017|work=The LGBT Sentinel|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Hill |first1=Zahara |title=rincess Nokia On Being Sexually Fluid And Making Music For Girls With The 'Delusional Confidence Of Barbra Streisand' |url=https://blavity.com/princess-nokia-on-being-sexually-fluid-and-making-music-for-girls-with-the-delusional-confidence-of-barbra-streisand?category1=music&subCat=culture |website=Blavity |date=20 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrasqueri also opened up about their identity as a [[Gender variance|gender non-conforming]] person and uses both they/them as well as she/her pronouns.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sanders |first1=Wren |title=Out Loud: Princess Nokia Is Done Explaining Themself |url=https://www.them.us/story/princess-nokia-interview-everything-sucks-everything-is-beautiful |website=Them |date=26 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stone |first1=Avery |title=King Princess Is Making Queer Pop Anthems for the Next Generation |url=https://www.vice.com/en_au/article/8xwedz/king-princess-cheap-queen-interview-profile-v26n4 |website=Vice |date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ushe |first1=Naledi |title=Princess Nokia Opens Up About Being a Gender Non-Conforming Artist in 'Playboy' Equality Issue |url=https://okmagazine.com/photos/princess-nokia-gender-non-conforming-artist-playboy-equality/ |website=OK Magazine |date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Studio albums ===\n*''Metallic Butterfly'' (2014, in 2018 was released a deluxe edition)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8490309/princess-nokia-metallic-butterfly-reissue|title=Princess Nokia Re-Issues 'Metallic Butterfly'|date=2018-12-14|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n*''[[1992 Deluxe]]'' (2017, as a deluxe edition of their EP of the same title)\n*''Everything Sucks'' (2020)\n*''[[Everything is Beautiful (Princess Nokia album)|Everything is Beautiful]]'' (2020)\n\n=== EP ===\n\n* ''1992'' (2016)\n* ''G.O.A.T.'' (2017)\n\n=== Mixtapes ===\n\n* ''Honeysuckle'' (2015, as Destiny)\n*''A Girl Cried Red'' (2018)\n\n=== Guest appearances ===\n* [[Ratking (group)|Ratking]] \u2013 \"Puerto Rican Judo\" from ''[[So It Goes (Ratking album)|So It Goes]]'' (2014)\n* [[Mykki Blanco]] \u2013 \"Wish You Would\" from ''Spring/Summer 2014'' (2014)\n* Ratking \u2013 \"Steep Tech\" from ''[[700-Fill]]'' (2015)\n* [[K. Michelle]] \u2013 \"Outro\" from ''[[Kimberly: The People I Used to Know]]'' (2017)\n* [[Show Me the Body]] \u2013 \"Spit\" from ''Corpus I'' (2017)\n* Josh Forehead \u2013 \"Fanta\" from ''Summer 2014'' (2017)\n* [[Silverstein (band)|Silverstein]] - \"Madness\" from ''[[A Beautiful Place to Drown]]'' (2020)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n===Sweden GAFFA Awards===\nDelivered since 2010, the GAFFA Awards (Swedish: GAFFA Priset) are a Swedish award that rewards popular music awarded by the magazine of the same name.\n{{awards table}}\n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 2018\n| Themself\n| Best Foreign New Act\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://gaffa.se/nyhet/124897/gaffa-priset-2018-och-de-nominerade-aer/|title=GAFFA-Priset 2018 \u2013 och de nominerade \u00e4r ...|work=GAFFA|access-date=September 3, 2019 |location=Sweden|language=Swedish}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* [[List of self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers]]\n* [[Nuyorican]]\n* [[Puerto Ricans in New York City]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube | u = dnfrasqueri }}\n* [http://princessnokia.org/ Princess Nokia's official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bisexual feminists]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:Trip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Feminist rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Indie rappers]]\n[[Category:LGBT musicians from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:LGBT rappers]]\n[[Category:People of Afro-Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:People from East Harlem]]\n[[Category:People from the Lower East Side]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican rappers]]\n", "name_user": "186.96.211.119", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(SVA)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princess_Nokia"}
{"title_page": "Jimmy Conrad", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2014}}\n{{more footnotes|date=June 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Jimmy Conrad\n| image                = JimmyConrad 2006 MLS Cup.jpg\n| image_size           = 200\n| caption              =\n| fullname             = James P. Conrad\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1977|2|12}}\n| birth_place          = [[Arcadia, California]], United States\n| height               = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}\n| position             = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub          = [[San Francisco Glens]] (head coach)\n| clubnumber           =\n| collegeyears1 = 1994\u20131995 | college1 = [[San Diego State Aztecs men's soccer|San Diego State Aztecs]]\n| collegeyears2 = 1996\u20131997 | college2 = [[UCLA Bruins men's soccer|UCLA Bruins]]\n| years1 = 1998 | clubs1 = [[San Diego Flash]] | caps1 = 26 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 1999\u20132002 | clubs2 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]] | caps2 = 84 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 1999 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[San Francisco Seals (soccer)|San Francisco Bay Seals]] (loan) | caps3 = 1 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1999 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[MLS Pro-40]] (loan) | caps4 = 5 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2000 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Lech Pozna\u0144]] (loan) | caps5 = 8 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2003\u20132010 | clubs6 = [[Kansas City Wizards]] | caps6 = 204 | goals6 = 17\n| years7 = 2011 | clubs7 = [[Chivas USA]] | caps7 = 2 | goals7 = 1 <!--\n\nThis section of the infobox is for senior competition in officially sanctioned football leagues\n\n[[Hashtag United F.C.]] doesn't qualify\n\n-->| totalcaps            = 325\n| totalgoals           = 22\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\u20132010 | nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 27 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2011\n| managerclubs1 = [[Chivas USA]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2018\u20132019\n| managerclubs2 = [[San Francisco Glens]] (associate)\n| manageryears3 = 2020\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[San Francisco Glens]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n|module={{infobox YouTube personality|embed=yes\n| pseudonym            = \n| channel_url          = https://m.youtube.com/user/TheJimmyConrad\n| channel_display_name = Jimmy Conrad\n| years_active         = 2016\u2013present\n| genre                = \n| subscribers          = 131,020\n| subscriber_date      = {{date}}\n| views                = 15,063,926\n| view_date            = {{date}}\n| network              = \n| associated_acts      = \n| catchphrase(s)       = \n| silver_button        = yes\n| silver_year          = \n| gold_button          = \n| gold_year            = \n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = \n}}\n\n}}\n\n'''James P. Conrad''' (born February 12, 1977) is an American retired [[soccer]] player who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]]. During his 13-year MLS career, he was four-time [[MLS Best XI]] and the 2005 [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|MLS Defender of the Year]]. He also earned 27 [[cap (sports)|caps]] with the [[United States men's national soccer team]] and went to the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. After his playing career Conrad has worked in the media industry <ref>{{cite web|last=Laird |first=Sam |url=http://mashable.com/2014/04/19/soccer-youtube-jimmy-conrad-kick-tv/#0nOvi.RJSkqM |title=A Soccer Star's Transition From the Pitch to YouTube |publisher=Mashable |date=2014-04-20 |accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> and currently stars on his [[YouTube]] channel [https://www.youtube.com/user/TheJimmyConrad Jimmy Conrad]. He currently serves as the head coach of [[USL League Two]] side [[San Francisco Glens]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===High school and college===\nBorn in [[Arcadia, California]], Conrad attended [[Temple City High School]] in [[Temple City, California]] and was a four-year letterman in soccer. Conrad played at [[San Diego State University]] in 1994 and 1995, and then transferred to the [[University of California, Los Angeles]]. While playing for UCLA, he was a member of the 1997 [[NCAA Men's Soccer Championship|NCAA Championship]] team.\n\n===Professional===\nUndrafted by MLS, Conrad had an unsuccessful trial with the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]].  However, the Galaxy coaching staff recommended he play for one of their affiliated lower division teams.  Consequently, Conrad contacted the now-defunct [[San Diego Flash]] of the [[USL First Division|A-League]] which gave him a contract.  In 1999, [[Brian Quinn (soccer)|Brian Quinn]] became the head coach of the [[San Jose Clash]].  When Quinn began searching for an additional defender and goalkeeper for the Clash, [[Ralf Wilhelms]], head coach of the Flash and a former teammate of Quinn on the [[San Diego Sockers (1974\u201396)|San Diego Sockers]], recommended Conrad and Flash goalkeeper [[Joe Cannon (soccer)|Joe Cannon]].<ref>[http://www.signonsandiego.com/sports/20060118-9999-lz1s18soccr-1.html Often-overlooked Jimmy Conrad, now with national team, has proved doubters wrong]</ref>  The Clash signed Conrad that year.  He played with the club, later re-branded as the Earthquakes, for four seasons, helping them to the [[MLS Cup]] in 2001. In 2000, he also played for [[Lech Pozna\u0144]] in Poland.\n\nIn 2003, Conrad was traded to the Wizards for a second-round draft pick, which the 'Quakes used to select [[Arturo \u00c1lvarez (footballer, born 1985)|Arturo Alvarez]]. Conrad's stock rose while with Kansas City; never a big scorer, he tallied four goals during his first season (he has ten in his MLS career). In 2004, he helped the Wizards to the [[US Open Cup]] and the MLS Cup Final as the leader of the league's stingiest defense and was named to the league's [[MLS Best XI|Best XI]] and was a finalist for [[MLS Defender of the Year Award]]. He won the award a year later.\n\nDespite rumors of a possible European transfer following the Wizards' disappointing 2006 season, Conrad renewed his contract with the Wizards beginning the 2007 season, and new head coach [[Curt Onalfo]] rewarded him the club captaincy.\n\nConrad was out of contract after the [[2010 MLS season]] and elected to participate in the [[2010 MLS Re-Entry Draft]]. On December 15, 2010 Conrad was selected by [[Chivas USA]] in Stage 2 of the Re-Entry draft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/wolff-angel-selected-re-entry-stage-2-draft |title=Wolff goes 1st in Stage 2 Re-Entry Draft, \u00c1ngel to LA  |work=www.mlssoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=15 December 2010 |accessdate=23 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219135941/http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/wolff-angel-selected-re-entry-stage-2-draft |archivedate=19 December 2010 |quote=Wolff's former Kansas City teammate Jimmy Conrad also went in the early going on Wednesday, taken second overall by Chivas USA. Conrad spent the last eight seasons in Kansas City and was a perennial All-Star during his time there, and could join a Chivas USA team largely in-flux after missing the postseason in 2010.}}</ref> He made his debut, and scored his first goal for his new team on March 19, 2011 in their first game of the 2011 MLS season \u2013 ironically against his old club, [[Sporting Kansas City]].<ref>[http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/bravos-debut-double-sporting-sinks-chivas-usa Bravo's debut double for Sporting sinks Chivas USA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322041022/http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/bravos-debut-double-sporting-sinks-chivas-usa |date=2011-03-22 }}</ref>\n\nAfter struggling with injury during the 2011 season, and suffering from side effects of six concussions, Jimmy Conrad announced his retirement from professional soccer on August 18, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ratterree |first=Alicia |url=http://www.thegoatparade.com/2011/8/17/2369285/jimmy-conrad-retires-from-mls |title=Jimmy Conrad Retires from MLS |publisher=The Goat Parade |date=2011-08-17 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nConrad received his first cap for the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] on July 7, 2005, in a [[2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] match against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]]. Less than one year later, Conrad made the U.S. roster for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. In Germany, Conrad came in as a substitute against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the team's 1\u20131 draw with the eventual champions, and played all ninety minutes against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]. On January 20, 2007, Conrad captained the national team for the second time, where the United States hosted an international [[Exhibition game|friendly]] with [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]. The U.S. won that match 3\u20131. On February 7, 2007, in an international friendly with [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], Conrad was named the [[Man of the Match]]. He scored his first-ever goal for the U.S. in the fifty-second minute of that match. On June 25, 2009, after not having played with the national team in previous qualifying, Conrad was named to the U.S. squad for the upcoming [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usmen.american-soccer-news.com/?p=250|title=Article from American Soccer News|publisher=Usmen.american-soccer-news.com|accessdate=2012-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224183627/http://usmen.american-soccer-news.com/?p=250|archive-date=2012-02-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching===\nIn September 2018, Conrad became technical director and head associate coach of the [[San Francisco Glens]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Redd |first=Matt |url=https://www.uslleaguetwo.com/news_article/show/968175 |title=Jimmy Conrad Brings Creative, Professional Experience To San Francisco |publisher=USL League Two |date=2018-11-19 |accessdate=2018-11-25}}</ref> He was named head coach of the Glens ahead of the 2020 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfglens.com/news_article/show/1083370 |title=JIMMY CONRAD TO SUCCEED JAVIER AYALA-HIL AS 2020 SF GLENS COACH |website=sfglens.com |date=February 4, 2020 |accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==='''Honors'''===\n'''San Jose Earthquakes'''\n*[[MLS Cup]]: 2001\n\n'''Kansas City Wzards'''\n*[[U.S. Open Cup]]: 2004\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[MLS Best XI]] (4): 2004, 2005, 2006, 2008\n*[[MLS Defender of the Year]]: 2005\n*[[Major League All Star Game]]: 2004, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2008, 2009\n*Sporting Legend: Class of 2014 <ref>{{cite web |title=Sporting Legends- Jimmy Conrad |url=https://www.sportingkc.com/sportinglegends/jimmy-conrad |website=Sporting KC |publisher=MLS Digital |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MLS|jimmy-conrad}}\n* [http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/archive?columnist=45&root=mls&cc=5901 Articles by Jimmy Conrad on ESPN Soccernet]\n* {{FIFA|229823}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/TheJimmyConrad Jimmy Conrad's YouTube Channel]\n* {{NFT player|11880}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Awards\n|bg = Gold\n|fg = Black\n|bordercolor = White\n|list1=\n{{2004 MLS Best XI}}\n{{MLS Defender of the Year}}\n{{2005 MLS Best XI}}\n{{2006 MLS Best XI}}\n{{2008 MLS Best XI}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= United States squads\n|bg= white\n|fg= #002868\n|bordercolor= #BF0A30\n|list1=\n{{United States Squad 2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{United States Squad 2006 World Cup}}\n{{United States Squad 2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{United States Squad 2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n}}\n{{1997 UCLA Bruins men's soccer navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conrad, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Arcadia, California]]\n[[Category:People from Temple City, California]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from California]]\n[[Category:San Diego Flash players]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Seals (soccer) players]]\n[[Category:MLS Pro-40 players]]\n[[Category:Sporting Kansas City players]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Lech Pozna\u0144 players]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:San Diego State Aztecs men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:CONCACAF Gold Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:United States men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:USISL A-League players]]\n[[Category:USL A-League players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Poland]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Poland]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=June 2014}}\n{{more footnotes|date=June 2014}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                 = Jimmy Conrad\n| image                = JimmyConrad 2006 MLS Cup.jpg\n| image_size           = 200\n| caption              =\n| fullname             = James P. Conrad\n| birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1977|2|12}}\n| birth_place          = [[Arcadia, California]], United States\n| height               = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}\n| position             = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub          = [[San Francisco Glens]] (head coach)\n| clubnumber           =\n| collegeyears1 = 1994\u20131995 | college1 = [[San Diego State Aztecs men's soccer|San Diego State Aztecs]]\n| collegeyears2 = 1996\u20131997 | college2 = [[UCLA Bruins men's soccer|UCLA Bruins]]\n| years1 = 1998 | clubs1 = [[San Diego Flash]] | caps1 = 26 | goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 1999\u20132002 | clubs2 = [[San Jose Earthquakes]] | caps2 = 84 | goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 1999 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[San Francisco Seals (soccer)|San Francisco Bay Seals]] (loan) | caps3 = 1 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1999 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[MLS Pro-40]] (loan) | caps4 = 5 | goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2000 | clubs5 = \u2192 [[Lech Pozna\u0144]] (loan) | caps5 = 8 | goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2003\u20132010 | clubs6 = [[Kansas City Wizards]] | caps6 = 204 | goals6 = 17\n| years7 = 2011 | clubs7 = [[Chivas USA]] | caps7 = 2 | goals7 = 1 <!--\n\nThis section of the infobox is for senior competition in officially sanctioned football leagues\n\n[[Hashtag United F.C.]] doesn't qualify\n\n-->| totalcaps            = 325\n| totalgoals           = 22\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\u20132010 | nationalteam1 = [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 27 | nationalgoals1 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2011\n| managerclubs1 = [[Chivas USA]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2018\u20132019\n| managerclubs2 = [[San Francisco Glens]] (associate)\n| manageryears3 = 2020\u2013\n| managerclubs3 = [[San Francisco Glens]]\n| medaltemplates       =\n|module={{infobox YouTube personality|embed=yes\n| pseudonym            = \n| channel_url          = https://m.youtube.com/user/TheJimmyConrad\n| channel_display_name = Jimmy Conrad\n| years_active         = 2016\u2013present\n| genre                = \n| subscribers          = 131,020\n| subscriber_date      = {{date}}\n| views                = 15,063,926\n| view_date            = {{date}}\n| network              = \n| associated_acts      = \n| catchphrase(s)       = \n| silver_button        = yes\n| silver_year          = \n| gold_button          = \n| gold_year            = \n| diamond_button       = \n| diamond_year         = \n| ruby_button          = \n| ruby_year            = \n| stats_update         = \n}}\n\n}}\n\n'''James P. Conrad''' (born February 12, 1977) is an American retired [[soccer]] player who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]]. During his 13-year MLS career, he was four-time [[MLS Best XI]] and the 2005 [[MLS Defender of the Year Award|MLS Defender of the Year]]. He also earned 27 [[cap (sports)|caps]] with the [[United States men's national soccer team]] and went to the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. After his playing career Conrad has worked in the media industry <ref>{{cite web|last=Laird |first=Sam |url=http://mashable.com/2014/04/19/soccer-youtube-jimmy-conrad-kick-tv/#0nOvi.RJSkqM |title=A Soccer Star's Transition From the Pitch to YouTube |publisher=Mashable |date=2014-04-20 |accessdate=2016-10-24}}</ref> and currently stars on his [[YouTube]] channel [https://www.youtube.com/user/TheJimmyConrad Jimmy Conrad]. He currently serves as the head coach of [[USL League Two]] side [[San Francisco Glens]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===High school and college===\nBorn in [[Arcadia, California]], Conrad attended [[Temple City High School]] in [[Temple City, California]] and was a four-year letterman in soccer. Conrad played at [[San Diego State University]] in 1994 and 1995, and then transferred to the [[University of California, Los Angeles]]. While playing for UCLA, he was a member of the 1997 [[NCAA Men's Soccer Championship|NCAA Championship]] team.\n\n===Professional===\nUndrafted by MLS, Conrad had an unsuccessful trial with the [[Los Angeles Galaxy]].  However, the Galaxy coaching staff recommended he play for one of their affiliated lower division teams.  Consequently, Conrad contacted the now-defunct [[San Diego Flash]] of the [[USL First Division|A-League]] which gave him a contract.  In 1999, [[Brian Quinn (soccer)|Brian Quinn]] became the head coach of the [[San Jose Clash]].  When Quinn began searching for an additional defender and goalkeeper for the Clash, [[Ralf Wilhelms]], head coach of the Flash and a former teammate of Quinn on the [[San Diego Sockers (1974\u201396)|San Diego Sockers]], recommended Conrad and Flash goalkeeper [[Joe Cannon (soccer)|Joe Cannon]].<ref>[http://www.signonsandiego.com/sports/20060118-9999-lz1s18soccr-1.html Often-overlooked Jimmy Conrad, now with national team, has proved doubters wrong]</ref>  The Clash signed Conrad that year.  He played with the club, later re-branded as the Earthquakes, for four seasons, helping them to the [[MLS Cup]] in 2001. In 2000, he also played for [[Lech Pozna\u0144]] in Poland.\n\nIn 2003, Conrad was traded to the Wizards for a second-round draft pick, which the 'Quakes used to select [[Arturo \u00c1lvarez (footballer, born 1985)|Arturo Alvarez]]. Conrad's stock rose while with Kansas City; never a big scorer, he tallied four goals during his first season (he has ten in his MLS career). In 2004, he helped the Wizards to the [[US Open Cup]] and the MLS Cup Final as the leader of the league's stingiest defense and was named to the league's [[MLS Best XI|Best XI]] and was a finalist for [[MLS Defender of the Year Award]]. He won the award a year later.\n\nDespite rumors of a possible European transfer following the Wizards' disappointing 2006 season, Conrad renewed his contract with the Wizards beginning the 2007 season, and new head coach [[Curt Onalfo]] rewarded him the club captaincy.\n\nConrad was out of contract after the [[2010 MLS season]] and elected to participate in the [[2010 MLS Re-Entry Draft]]. On December 15, 2010 Conrad was selected by [[Chivas USA]] in Stage 2 of the Re-Entry draft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/wolff-angel-selected-re-entry-stage-2-draft |title=Wolff goes 1st in Stage 2 Re-Entry Draft, \u00c1ngel to LA  |work=www.mlssoccer.com |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=15 December 2010 |accessdate=23 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101219135941/http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/wolff-angel-selected-re-entry-stage-2-draft |archivedate=19 December 2010 |quote=Wolff's former Kansas City teammate Jimmy Conrad also went in the early going on Wednesday, taken second overall by Chivas USA. Conrad spent the last eight seasons in Kansas City and was a perennial All-Star during his time there, and could join a Chivas USA team largely in-flux after missing the postseason in 2010.}}</ref> He made his debut, and scored his first goal for his new team on March 19, 2011 in their first game of the 2011 MLS season \u2013 ironically against his old club, [[Sporting Kansas City]].<ref>[http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/bravos-debut-double-sporting-sinks-chivas-usa Bravo's debut double for Sporting sinks Chivas USA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322041022/http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/bravos-debut-double-sporting-sinks-chivas-usa |date=2011-03-22 }}</ref>\n\nAfter struggling with injury during the 2011 season, and suffering from side effects of six concussions, Jimmy Conrad announced his retirement from professional soccer on August 18, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ratterree |first=Alicia |url=http://www.thegoatparade.com/2011/8/17/2369285/jimmy-conrad-retires-from-mls |title=Jimmy Conrad Retires from MLS |publisher=The Goat Parade |date=2011-08-17 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nConrad received his first cap for the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] on July 7, 2005, in a [[2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] match against [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]]. Less than one year later, Conrad made the U.S. roster for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. In Germany, Conrad came in as a substitute against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the team's 1\u20131 draw with the eventual champions, and played all ninety minutes against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]. On January 20, 2007, Conrad captained the national team for the second time, where the United States hosted an international [[Exhibition game|friendly]] with [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]]. The U.S. won that match 3\u20131. On February 7, 2007, in an international friendly with [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], Conrad was named the [[Man of the Match]]. He scored his first-ever goal for the U.S. in the fifty-second minute of that match. On June 25, 2009, after not having played with the national team in previous qualifying, Conrad was named to the U.S. squad for the upcoming [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usmen.american-soccer-news.com/?p=250|title=Article from American Soccer News|publisher=Usmen.american-soccer-news.com|accessdate=2012-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224183627/http://usmen.american-soccer-news.com/?p=250|archive-date=2012-02-24|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Coaching===\nIn September 2018, Conrad became technical director and head associate coach of the [[San Francisco Glens]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Redd |first=Matt |url=https://www.uslleaguetwo.com/news_article/show/968175 |title=Jimmy Conrad Brings Creative, Professional Experience To San Francisco |publisher=USL League Two |date=2018-11-19 |accessdate=2018-11-25}}</ref> He was named head coach of the Glens ahead of the 2020 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfglens.com/news_article/show/1083370 |title=JIMMY CONRAD TO SUCCEED JAVIER AYALA-HIL AS 2020 SF GLENS COACH |website=sfglens.com |date=February 4, 2020 |accessdate=February 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==='''Honors'''===\n'''Kansas City Wzards'''\n*[[U.S. Open Cup]]: 2004\n\n'''Individual'''\n[[MLS Best XI]] (4): 2004, 2005, 2006, 2008\n[[MLS Defender of the Year]]: 2005\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MLS|jimmy-conrad}}\n* [http://soccernet.espn.go.com/columns/archive?columnist=45&root=mls&cc=5901 Articles by Jimmy Conrad on ESPN Soccernet]\n* {{FIFA|229823}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/TheJimmyConrad Jimmy Conrad's YouTube Channel]\n* {{NFT player|11880}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Awards\n|bg = Gold\n|fg = Black\n|bordercolor = White\n|list1=\n{{2004 MLS Best XI}}\n{{MLS Defender of the Year}}\n{{2005 MLS Best XI}}\n{{2006 MLS Best XI}}\n{{2008 MLS Best XI}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= United States squads\n|bg= white\n|fg= #002868\n|bordercolor= #BF0A30\n|list1=\n{{United States Squad 2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n{{United States Squad 2006 World Cup}}\n{{United States Squad 2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{United States Squad 2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup}}\n}}\n{{1997 UCLA Bruins men's soccer navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conrad, Jimmy}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Arcadia, California]]\n[[Category:People from Temple City, California]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate soccer players]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from California]]\n[[Category:San Diego Flash players]]\n[[Category:San Jose Earthquakes players]]\n[[Category:San Francisco Seals (soccer) players]]\n[[Category:MLS Pro-40 players]]\n[[Category:Sporting Kansas City players]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Lech Pozna\u0144 players]]\n[[Category:UCLA Bruins men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:San Diego State Aztecs men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:CONCACAF Gold Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:2005 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2007 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:2009 CONCACAF Gold Cup players]]\n[[Category:United States men's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:USISL A-League players]]\n[[Category:USL A-League players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Poland]]\n[[Category:American expatriate sportspeople in Poland]]\n[[Category:Chivas USA non-playing staff]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n", "name_user": "Wikipert22", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmy_Conrad"}
{"title_page": "Teapot Dome scandal", "text_new": "{{redirect|Teapot Dome}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|1921\u20131923 U.S. Cabinet bribery scandal}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n[[File:Edward Doheny Testifying 2 crop.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Oil businessman [[Edward L. Doheny]] (at table, second from right) testifying before the Senate committee investigating the Teapot Dome oil leases, 1924]]\n\nThe '''Teapot Dome scandal''' was a [[bribery]] scandal involving the administration of United States President [[Warren G. Harding]] from 1921 to 1923. [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Albert Bacon Fall]] had leased [[United States Navy|Navy]] [[petroleum]] reserves at [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome]] in [[Wyoming]], and two locations in [[California]], to private oil companies at low rates without competitive bidding. The leases were the subject of a seminal investigation by Senator [[Thomas J. Walsh]]. Convicted of accepting bribes from the oil companies, Fall became the first [[Cabinet of the United States|presidential cabinet]] member to go to prison; no one was convicted of paying the bribes.\n\nBefore the [[Watergate scandal]], Teapot Dome was regarded as the \"greatest and most sensational [[List of federal political scandals in the United States|scandal in the history of American politics]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |title=Graft and Oil: How Teapot Dome Became the Greatest Political Scandal of its Time |last=Cherny |first=Robert W |work=History Now |publisher=[[Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History]] |accessdate=May 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709015531/http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |archivedate=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> It damaged the reputation of the Harding administration, which was already severely diminished by its controversial handling of the [[Great Railroad Strike of 1922]] and Harding's veto of the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act|Bonus Bill]] in 1922.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.presidentprofiles.com/Grant-Eisenhower/Warren-G-Harding-Domestic-and-foreign-affairs.html | title = Grant-Eisenhower | contribution = Warren G Harding: Domestic & foreign affairs | publisher = President profiles}}.</ref> Congress subsequently passed legislation, enduring to this day, giving subpoena power to the House and Senate for review of tax records of any US citizen without regard to elected or appointed position, nor subject to White House interference.<ref name=Paletta9April>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-treasury-lawyers-discussed-trumps-tax-returns-before-democrats-request-mnuchin-says/2019/04/09/9693618e-5ad2-11e9-842d-7d3ed7eb3957_story.html |title=Mnuchin reveals White House lawyers consulted Treasury on Trump tax returns, despite law meant to limit political involvement |work=The Washington Post|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|first=Damian|last=Paletta}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Teapot Rock postcard crop.jpg|thumb|Teapot Dome around the time of the scandal, featuring Teapot Rock (from postcard c. 1922)]]\n\nIn the early 20th century, the U.S. Navy largely converted from [[coal]] to [[fuel oil]]. To ensure that the Navy would always have enough fuel available, several oil-producing areas were designated as naval oil reserves by [[William Howard Taft|President Taft]]. In 1921, President Harding issued an [[executive order]] that transferred control of [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome Oil Field]] in [[Natrona County, Wyoming]], and the [[Elk Hills Oil Field|Elk Hills]] and [[Buena Vista Oil Field]]s in [[Kern County, California]], from the [[United States Department of the Navy|Navy Department]] to the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]]. This was not implemented until 1922, when Interior Secretary Fall persuaded [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Edwin Denby (politician)|Edwin C. Denby]] to transfer control.\n\nLater in 1922, Interior Secretary Albert Fall leased the oil production rights at Teapot Dome to [[Harry Ford Sinclair|Harry F. Sinclair]] of Mammoth Oil, a subsidiary of [[Sinclair Oil Corporation]]. He also leased the Elk Hills reserve to [[Edward L. Doheny]] of [[Pan American Petroleum and Transport Company]]. Both leases were issued without competitive bidding. This manner of leasing was legal under the [[Mineral Leasing Act of 1920]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/ut/vernal_fo/lands___minerals.Par.6287.File.dat/MineralLeasingAct1920.pdf | title= Mineral Leasing Act of 1920 as Amended (re-transcribed 2007-08-07) | publisher= Bureau of Land Management, U.S. Department of the Interior | accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe lease terms were very favorable to the oil companies, which secretly made Fall a rich man. Fall had received a no-interest loan from Doheny of $100,000 (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|100000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn |US}}) in November 1921. He received other gifts from Doheny and Sinclair totaling about $404,000 (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|404000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn|US}}). This money changing hands was illegal, not the leases. Fall attempted to keep his actions secret, but the sudden improvement in his standard of living was suspect.\n\n==Investigation and outcome==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2017}}\nIn April 1922, a Wyoming oil operator wrote to his Senator, [[John B. Kendrick]], angered that Sinclair had been given a contract to the lands in a secret deal. Kendrick did not respond, but two days later on April 15, he introduced a resolution calling for an investigation of the deal.<ref>{{cite book | author = Davis, Margaret L | title= Dark Side of Fortune: Triumph and Scandal in the Life of Oil Tycoon Edward L. Doheny| publisher =[[University of California Press]]|year=2001|isbn=9780520927056|page=149|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=q65CsgOv7dMC&pg=PA149}}</ref> [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Senator [[Robert M. La Follette Sr.]] of [[Wisconsin]] led an investigation by the Senate Committee on Public Lands. At first, La Follette believed Fall was innocent. However, his suspicions were aroused after his own office in the [[Senate Office Building]] was ransacked.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/Senate_Investigates_the_Teapot_Dome_Scandal.htm|title=Senate Investigates the \"Teapot Dome\" Scandal |work= Historical Minutes: 1921\u20131940|publisher=Art & History, United States Senate}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Albert B. Fall with map background.jpg|thumb|[[Albert B. Fall]] was the first U.S. cabinet official sentenced to prison.]]\n\nDemocrat [[Thomas J. Walsh]] of [[Montana]], the most junior minority member, led a lengthy inquiry. For two years, Walsh pushed forward while Fall stepped backward, covering his tracks as he went. No evidence of wrongdoing was initially uncovered, as the leases were legal enough, but records kept disappearing mysteriously. Fall had made the leases appear legitimate, but his acceptance of the money was his undoing. By 1924, the remaining unanswered question was how Fall had become so rich so quickly and easily.\n\nMoney from the bribes had gone to Fall's cattle ranch and investments in his business. Finally, as the investigation was winding down with Fall apparently innocent, Walsh uncovered a piece of evidence Fall had failed to cover up: Doheny's $100,000 loan to Fall. This discovery broke open the scandal. Civil and criminal suits related to the scandal continued throughout the 1920s. In 1927, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] ruled that the oil leases had been corruptly obtained. The Court invalidated the Elk Hills lease in February 1927, and the Teapot Dome lease in October. Both reserves were returned to the Navy.<ref name=revenues/>\n\nIn 1929, Fall was found guilty of accepting bribes from Doheny. Conversely, in 1930, Doheny was acquitted of paying bribes to Fall. Further, Doheny's corporation foreclosed on Fall's home in [[Tularosa Basin]], New Mexico, because of \"unpaid loans\" that turned out to be that same $100,000 bribe. Sinclair served six months in jail on a charge of [[jury tampering]].<ref>{{cite book |last=McCartney |first=Laton |title=The Teapot Dome Scandal: How Big Oil Bought the Harding White House and Tried to Steal the Country |location=New York |publisher=[[Random House]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4000-6316-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/teapotdomescanda00mcca }}</ref>\n\nAlthough Fall was to blame for this scandal, Harding's reputation was sullied because of his involvement with the wrong people. Evidence proving Fall's guilt only arose after Harding's death in 1923.<ref>{{cite book|last1=MacDonald|first1=Scott B.|last2=Hughes|first2=Jane E.|title=Separating Fools from Their Money: A History of American Financial Scandals|orig-year=1st pub. 2007|publisher=Transaction|location=New Brunswick, N.J.|isbn=978-0-7658-0356-6|date=2015|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/separat_mac_2007_00_2620}}</ref>\n\nAnother significant outcome was the Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[McGrain v. Daugherty]]'' (1927) which, for the first time, explicitly established that [[Congress of the United States|Congress]] had the power to compel testimony.<ref name=\"oyez\">{{Cite web | title = McGrain v. Daugherty | publisher = Oyez.org | url = https://www.oyez.org/cases/1901-1939/1924/1924_28 | accessdate = 2 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe oil field was then idled for 49 years, but went back into production in 1976. After earning over $569 million in revenue having extracted {{convert|22|e6oilbbl|lk=in}} of oil over the previous 39 years, in February 2015, the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] sold the oil field for $45 million to New York-based Stranded Oil Resources Corp.<ref name=revenues>[http://www.denverpost.com/2015/01/30/government-sells-scandalized-teapot-dome-oilfield-for-45-million Government sells scandalized Teapot Dome oilfield for $45 million], ''[[Denver Post]]'', [[Associated Press]]'', January 30, 2015. Retrieved 4 June 2017.</ref>\n\n==Comparison==\n\nThe Teapot Dome scandal has historically been regarded as the worst such scandal in the United States \u2013 the \"[[high water mark]]\" of cabinet corruption. It is often used as a benchmark for comparison with subsequent scandals. In particular it has been compared to the [[Watergate scandal]], in which a cabinet member, Attorney General [[John N. Mitchell]], went to prison, the second time in American history that a member of cabinet has been incarcerated.<ref>{{cite book|title=Watergate & the Teapot Dome Scandal: The History and Legacy of America's Most Notorious Government Scandals|date=November 2, 2016|publisher=Charles River Editors |edition=Kindle |asin=B01N9IMB2P}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Uncovering a Coverup on Teapot Dome|last=Roberts|first=Chalmers M.|date=June 9, 1977|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Little Green House on K Street]]\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* Bates, J. Leonard. ''The Origins of Teapot Dome''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 1963.\n* Bennett, Leslie E. [http://academic.brooklyn.cuny.edu/history/johnson/teapotdome.htm \"One Lesson From History: Appointment of Special Counsel and the Investigation of the Teapot Dome Scandal\"]. Washington, D.C.: Brookings Institution, 1999.\n* Ise, John. ''The United States Oil Policy''. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press, 1926.\n* Murphy, Blakely M. (ed.) ''Conservation of Oil and Gas: A Legal History''. Chicago: Section of Mineral Law, American Bar Association, 1949.\n* [[Burl Noggle|Noggle, Burl]]. ''Teapot Dome: Oil and Politics in the 1920s''. Baton Rouge, LA: Louisiana State University Press, 1962.\n* Werner, M. R. and Starr, John. ''Teapot Dome''. New York: Viking Press, 1959.\n\n{{US federal public corruption law}}\n{{US history}}\n{{Special Prosecutors and Independent Counsels of the U.S.}}\n\n{{coord|43.2885808|N|106.1733516|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Teapot Dome scandal| ]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political corruption scandals in the United States]]\n[[Category:1920s in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bribery scandals]]\n[[Category:Cover-ups]]\n[[Category:History of Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:History of the San Joaquin Valley]]\n[[Category:History of Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Natrona County, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Oil fields in Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in California]]\n[[Category:Sinclair Oil Corporation]]\n[[Category:1922 in California]]\n[[Category:1923 in California]]\n[[Category:1922 in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:1923 in Wyoming]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Teapot Dome}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Short description|1921\u20131923 U.S. Cabinet bribery scandal}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2019}}\n[[File:Edward Doheny Testifying 2 crop.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Oil businessman [[Edward L. Doheny]] (at table, second from right) testifying before the Senate committee investigating the Teapot Dome oil leases, 1924]]\n\nThe '''Teapot Dome scandal''' was a bribery scandal involving the administration of United States President [[Warren G. Harding]] from 1921 to 1923. [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]] [[Albert Bacon Fall]] had leased [[United States Navy|Navy]] [[petroleum]] reserves at [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome]] in [[Wyoming]], and two locations in [[California]], to private oil companies at low rates without competitive bidding. The leases were the subject of a seminal investigation by Senator [[Thomas J. Walsh]]. Convicted of accepting bribes from the oil companies, Fall became the first [[Cabinet of the United States|presidential cabinet]] member to go to prison; no one was convicted of paying the bribes.\n\nBefore the [[Watergate scandal]], Teapot Dome was regarded as the \"greatest and most sensational [[List of federal political scandals in the United States|scandal in the history of American politics]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |title=Graft and Oil: How Teapot Dome Became the Greatest Political Scandal of its Time |last=Cherny |first=Robert W |work=History Now |publisher=[[Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History]] |accessdate=May 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709015531/http://www.gilderlehrman.org/historynow/historian5.php |archivedate=July 9, 2010 }}</ref> It damaged the reputation of the Harding administration, which was already severely diminished by its controversial handling of the [[Great Railroad Strike of 1922]] and Harding's veto of the [[World War Adjusted Compensation Act|Bonus Bill]] in 1922.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.presidentprofiles.com/Grant-Eisenhower/Warren-G-Harding-Domestic-and-foreign-affairs.html | title = Grant-Eisenhower | contribution = Warren G Harding: Domestic & foreign affairs | publisher = President profiles}}.</ref> Congress subsequently passed legislation, enduring to this day, giving subpoena power to the House and Senate for review of tax records of any US citizen without regard to elected or appointed position, nor subject to White House interference.<ref name=Paletta9April>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/white-house-treasury-lawyers-discussed-trumps-tax-returns-before-democrats-request-mnuchin-says/2019/04/09/9693618e-5ad2-11e9-842d-7d3ed7eb3957_story.html |title=Mnuchin reveals White House lawyers consulted Treasury on Trump tax returns, despite law meant to limit political involvement |work=The Washington Post|date=9 April 2019|accessdate=9 April 2019|first=Damian|last=Paletta}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Teapot Rock postcard crop.jpg|thumb|Teapot Dome around the time of the scandal, featuring Teapot Rock (from postcard c. 1922)]]\n\nIn the early 20th century, the U.S. Navy largely converted from [[coal]] to [[fuel oil]]. To ensure that the Navy would always have enough fuel available, several oil-producing areas were designated as naval oil reserves by [[William Howard Taft|President Taft]]. In 1921, President Harding issued an [[executive order]] that transferred control of [[Teapot Rock|Teapot Dome Oil Field]] in [[Natrona County, Wyoming]], and the [[Elk Hills Oil Field|Elk Hills]] and [[Buena Vista Oil Field]]s in [[Kern County, California]], from the [[United States Department of the Navy|Navy Department]] to the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]]. This was not implemented until 1922, when Interior Secretary Fall persuaded [[United States Secretary of the Navy|Navy Secretary]] [[Edwin Denby (politician)|Edwin C. Denby]] to transfer control.\n\nLater in 1922, Interior Secretary Albert Fall leased the oil production rights at Teapot Dome to [[Harry Ford Sinclair|Harry F. Sinclair]] of Mammoth Oil, a subsidiary of [[Sinclair Oil Corporation]]. He also leased the Elk Hills reserve to [[Edward L. Doheny]] of [[Pan American Petroleum and Transport Company]]. Both leases were issued without competitive bidding. This manner of leasing was legal under the [[Mineral Leasing Act of 1920]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.blm.gov/pgdata/etc/medialib/blm/ut/vernal_fo/lands___minerals.Par.6287.File.dat/MineralLeasingAct1920.pdf | title= Mineral Leasing Act of 1920 as Amended (re-transcribed 2007-08-07) | publisher= Bureau of Land Management, U.S. Department of the Interior | accessdate=2014-09-08 }}</ref>\n\nThe lease terms were very favorable to the oil companies, which secretly made Fall a rich man. Fall had received a no-interest loan from Doheny of $100,000 (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|100000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn |US}}) in November 1921. He received other gifts from Doheny and Sinclair totaling about $404,000 (about ${{Format price|{{inflation|US|404000|1921}}}} today{{inflation-fn|US}}). This money changing hands was illegal, not the leases. Fall attempted to keep his actions secret, but the sudden improvement in his standard of living was suspect.\n\n==Investigation and outcome==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=April 2017}}\nIn April 1922, a Wyoming oil operator wrote to his Senator, [[John B. Kendrick]], angered that Sinclair had been given a contract to the lands in a secret deal. Kendrick did not respond, but two days later on April 15, he introduced a resolution calling for an investigation of the deal.<ref>{{cite book | author = Davis, Margaret L | title= Dark Side of Fortune: Triumph and Scandal in the Life of Oil Tycoon Edward L. Doheny| publisher =[[University of California Press]]|year=2001|isbn=9780520927056|page=149|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=q65CsgOv7dMC&pg=PA149}}</ref> [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Senator [[Robert M. La Follette Sr.]] of [[Wisconsin]] led an investigation by the Senate Committee on Public Lands. At first, La Follette believed Fall was innocent. However, his suspicions were aroused after his own office in the [[Senate Office Building]] was ransacked.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/Senate_Investigates_the_Teapot_Dome_Scandal.htm|title=Senate Investigates the \"Teapot Dome\" Scandal |work= Historical Minutes: 1921\u20131940|publisher=Art & History, United States Senate}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Albert B. Fall with map background.jpg|thumb|[[Albert B. Fall]] was the first U.S. cabinet official sentenced to prison.]]\n\nDemocrat [[Thomas J. Walsh]] of [[Montana]], the most junior minority member, led a lengthy inquiry. For two years, Walsh pushed forward while Fall stepped backward, covering his tracks as he went. No evidence of wrongdoing was initially uncovered, as the leases were legal enough, but records kept disappearing mysteriously. Fall had made the leases appear legitimate, but his acceptance of the money was his undoing. By 1924, the remaining unanswered question was how Fall had become so rich so quickly and easily.\n\nMoney from the bribes had gone to Fall's cattle ranch and investments in his business. Finally, as the investigation was winding down with Fall apparently innocent, Walsh uncovered a piece of evidence Fall had failed to cover up: Doheny's $100,000 loan to Fall. This discovery broke open the scandal. Civil and criminal suits related to the scandal continued throughout the 1920s. In 1927, the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] ruled that the oil leases had been corruptly obtained. The Court invalidated the Elk Hills lease in February 1927, and the Teapot Dome lease in October. Both reserves were returned to the Navy.<ref name=revenues/>\n\nIn 1929, Fall was found guilty of accepting bribes from Doheny. Conversely, in 1930, Doheny was acquitted of paying bribes to Fall. Further, Doheny's corporation foreclosed on Fall's home in [[Tularosa Basin]], New Mexico, because of \"unpaid loans\" that turned out to be that same $100,000 bribe. Sinclair served six months in jail on a charge of [[jury tampering]].<ref>{{cite book |last=McCartney |first=Laton |title=The Teapot Dome Scandal: How Big Oil Bought the Harding White House and Tried to Steal the Country |location=New York |publisher=[[Random House]] |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4000-6316-1 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/teapotdomescanda00mcca }}</ref>\n\nAlthough Fall was to blame for this scandal, Harding's reputation was sullied because of his involvement with the wrong people. Evidence proving Fall's guilt only arose after Harding's death in 1923.<ref>{{cite book|last1=MacDonald|first1=Scott B.|last2=Hughes|first2=Jane E.|title=Separating Fools from Their Money: A History of American Financial Scandals|orig-year=1st pub. 2007|publisher=Transaction|location=New Brunswick, N.J.|isbn=978-0-7658-0356-6|date=2015|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/separat_mac_2007_00_2620}}</ref>\n\nAnother significant outcome was the Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[McGrain v. Daugherty]]'' (1927) which, for the first time, explicitly established that [[Congress of the United States|Congress]] had the power to compel testimony.<ref name=\"oyez\">{{Cite web | title = McGrain v. Daugherty | publisher = Oyez.org | url = https://www.oyez.org/cases/1901-1939/1924/1924_28 | accessdate = 2 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe oil field was then idled for 49 years, but went back into production in 1976. After earning over $569 million in revenue having extracted {{convert|22|e6oilbbl|lk=in}} of oil over the previous 39 years, in February 2015, the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] sold the oil field for $45 million to New York-based Stranded Oil Resources Corp.<ref name=revenues>[http://www.denverpost.com/2015/01/30/government-sells-scandalized-teapot-dome-oilfield-for-45-million Government sells scandalized Teapot Dome oilfield for $45 million], ''[[Denver Post]]'', [[Associated Press]]'', January 30, 2015. Retrieved 4 June 2017.</ref>\n\n==Comparison==\n\nThe Teapot Dome scandal has historically been regarded as the worst such scandal in the United States \u2013 the \"[[high water mark]]\" of cabinet corruption. It is often used as a benchmark for comparison with subsequent scandals. In particular it has been compared to the [[Watergate scandal]], in which a cabinet member, Attorney General [[John N. Mitchell]], went to prison, the second time in American history that a member of cabinet has been incarcerated.<ref>{{cite book|title=Watergate & the Teapot Dome Scandal: The History and Legacy of America's Most Notorious Government Scandals|date=November 2, 2016|publisher=Charles River Editors |edition=Kindle |asin=B01N9IMB2P}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Uncovering a Coverup on Teapot Dome|last=Roberts|first=Chalmers M.|date=June 9, 1977|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Little Green House on K Street]]\n* [[List of federal political scandals in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* Bates, J. Leonard. ''The Origins of Teapot Dome''. Urbana, IL: University of Illinois Press, 1963.\n* Bennett, Leslie E. [http://academic.brooklyn.cuny.edu/history/johnson/teapotdome.htm \"One Lesson From History: Appointment of Special Counsel and the Investigation of the Teapot Dome Scandal\"]. Washington, D.C.: Brookings Institution, 1999.\n* Ise, John. ''The United States Oil Policy''. New Haven, CT: Yale University Press, 1926.\n* Murphy, Blakely M. (ed.) ''Conservation of Oil and Gas: A Legal History''. Chicago: Section of Mineral Law, American Bar Association, 1949.\n* [[Burl Noggle|Noggle, Burl]]. ''Teapot Dome: Oil and Politics in the 1920s''. Baton Rouge, LA: Louisiana State University Press, 1962.\n* Werner, M. R. and Starr, John. ''Teapot Dome''. New York: Viking Press, 1959.\n\n{{US federal public corruption law}}\n{{US history}}\n{{Special Prosecutors and Independent Counsels of the U.S.}}\n\n{{coord|43.2885808|N|106.1733516|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Teapot Dome scandal| ]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political corruption scandals in the United States]]\n[[Category:1920s in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bribery scandals]]\n[[Category:Cover-ups]]\n[[Category:History of Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:History of the San Joaquin Valley]]\n[[Category:History of Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Natrona County, Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Oil fields in Kern County, California]]\n[[Category:Petroleum in California]]\n[[Category:Sinclair Oil Corporation]]\n[[Category:1922 in California]]\n[[Category:1923 in California]]\n[[Category:1922 in Wyoming]]\n[