{"title_page": "Gamini Dissanayake", "text_new": "{{for|the Sri Lankan cricket umpire|Gamini Dissanayake (umpire)}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix  = [[The Honourable|Hon.]] \n| name              = Gamini Dissanayake\n| honorific-suffix  = \n| image             = Gamini Dissanayake.jpg\n| imagesize         = 250px\n| caption           = \n| office            = 10th [[Leader of the Opposition (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| president         = [[Dingiri Banda Wijetunga]] \n| primeminister     = [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]]\n| predecessor       = [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]\n| successor         = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start        = 25 August 1994 \n| term_end          = 24 October 1994\n| office1           = Minister of Mahaweli Development\n| president1        = [[J.R Jayawardena]] [[Ranasinghe Premadasa]]\n| primeminister1 =[[Ranasinghe Premadasa]]  [[Dingiri Banda Wijetunga]]\n| term_start1 = 1977\n| term_end1   = 1990\n| nationality       = Sri Lankan\n| constituency_MP3  = [[Nuwara Eliya-Maskeliya Electoral District|Nuwara Eliya-Maskeliya]]\n| parliament3       = Sri Lankan\n| predecessor3      = ''Constituency Established''\n| successor3        = ''Constituency Abolished''\n| term_start3       = 1977\n| term_end3         = 1988\n| constituency_MP4  = [[Nuwara Eliya Electoral District (1947\u20131989)|Nuwara Eliya]]\n| parliament4       = Sri Lankan\n| predecessor4      = [[D.J. Ranaweera]]\n| successor4        = ''Constituency Abolished''\n| term_start4       = 1970\n| term_end4         = 1977\n| constituency_MP2  = [[Nuwara Eliya Electoral District]]\n| parliament2       = Sri Lankan\n| majority2         = 73,790 Preferential Votes \n| predecessor2      = \n| successor2        = \n| term_start2       = 1989\n| term_end2         = 1994\n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = 20 March 1942\n| birth_place       = Kandy, Sri Lanka\n| religion          = [[Theravada Buddhism|Buddhist]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1994|10|24|1942|03|20}}\n| death_place       = Colombo, Sri Lanka (assassinated)\n| profession        = Lawyer\n| occupation        = Politician\n| years_active      = 1970\u20131994\n| alma_mater        = [[Trinity College, Kandy]],<br /> [[Cambridge University|Cambridge University, UK]] \n| spouse            = [[Shrima Dissanayake]]\n| children          = [[Navin Dissanayake|Navin]], [[Mayantha Dissanayake|Mayantha]], Varuni.\n| website           =              \n}}\n'''Dissanayake Mudiyanse Ralahamilage Lionel Gamini Dissanayake''' (known as '''Gamini Dissanayake'''; {{lang-si|\u0dbd\u0dba\u0db1\u0dbd\u0dca \u0d9c\u0dcf\u0db8\u0dd2\u0dab\u0dd2 \u0daf\u0dd2\u0dc3\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dcf\u0dba\u0d9a}},{{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bbe\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95}}; 20 March 1942 \u2013 24 October 1994) was a prominent Sri Lankan politician, a powerful minister of the [[United National Party]], and [[Leader of the Opposition (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the Opposition]]. He was designated as the UNP candidate in the [[1994 Sri Lankan presidential election|1994 presidential election]], but was then assassinated by the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE).\n\n==Early Life==\nHe was born in [[Kandy]] as the eldest son of a family of seven children to [[Andrew Dissanayake]] who served as an MP and a deputy minister in the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] government of [[Solomon Bandaranaike|S.W.R.D. Bandaranaike]]. His mother, Welegedara Samaratunga Kumarihamy of Kotmale. Born and bred in Kotmale, his basic values were cultivated in this rural milieu social surrounding and environment. The wealthy Dissanayake family resided in both [[Kandy]] as well as [[Nuwara Eliya]]. Dissanayake had his schooling at the prestigious [[Trinity College (Kandy)|Trinity College]] in Kandy, and received his tertiary education at the [[Sri Lanka Law College]]. Later in life, he completed an MPhil Degree in International Relations at [[Cambridge University]] UK.\n<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[File:Gamini Dissanayake statue.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Gamini Dissanayake statue at<br /> Viharamahadevi Park in Colombo]] -->\n\n==Political career==\nGamini Dissanayake won the 1970 elections and became a member of parliament under UNP candidature and was one of the 18 UNP members in the parliament at a time when his party has faced an humiliating defeat. He comfortably secured his Nuwaraeliya-Maskeliya multielectorate seat in the 1977 elections and was appointed as the minister of Mahaweli Development. Dissanyake spearheaded the [[Mahaweli Development programme|Mahaweli Development Project]]. This was a huge project which was expected to take 30 years to finish. But due to Dissanayake's skills he managed to finish the project within 6 years. The Mahaweli Development Project is the largest development project conducted in Sri Lanka after independence. The whole country was affected by the project which focused on irrigation, hydro power generation, agriculture, town & country development. Further it was criticised by the time as to introduce sinhala population into Tamil's motherland. Majority of the power generated for the local consumption is generated from these hydropower plants while an overwhelming majority of the rice cultivation in Sri Lanka is conducted in these [[Mahaweli]] areas.\n\nHe was the chairperson of the Sri Lanka Cricket Board in the early 1980s and helped his country to gain the Test Status in cricket. He played a pivotal role in signing the Indoo-Lanka Peace Accord in 1987. In 1989 he was re elected as a MP from Nuwaraeliya District securing the highest percentage of preferential votes obtained by any UNP MP. He was the Minister of Estate Development during Premadasa regime. He was not awarded a portfolio in 1990 cabinet reshuffle and remained as a back-seat MP in the parliament. Dissanayake was accused of abduction of Prof. Ralph Bultjens. Prof Rohan Goonarathne in an interview with Hasitha Kuruppu told that Dissanayake did that as Bultjens in his lectures accused Dissanayake for swindling of money.<ref>GunaratnaRohan. Interview with Hasitha Kuruppu. Ceylontoday. November 2013</ref> Later he was acquitted from the courts.\n\nHe played a major role in the aborted impeachment motion against President Premadasa and as a result was expelled from UNP in 1992. In the same year Dissanayaka joined Lalith Athulathmudali to form United National Democratic Front (DUNF) which was a rising political force of that era. Dissanayaka contested to Kandy District at 1993 provincial council elections and became a member of the Central Provincial Council. After the assassination of Athulathmudali, Dissanayake became the leader of DUNF. Later he rejoined UNP and was appointed to the parliament as a national list MP and was offered a vital portfolio in the Wijethunga Government. In 1994 PA came to power defeating UNP when Dissanayaka was re elected as a member of parliament from Kandy District. In a contest held among UNP MPs to choose the opposition leader Dissanayaka recorded a comfortable victory over Ranil Wickramasinghe.\n\n==Assassination==\nWhen President [[Dingiri Banda Wijetunga|D.B. Wijetunga]] indicated he would not run in the [[1994 Sri Lankan presidential election|1994 presidential election]], Dissanayake was selected as the UNP candidate at the same time he was the Leader of the Opposition in parliament.  This was cut short when he was assassinated by a [[female suicide bomber]] of the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE) while he was addressing an election meeting at Thotalanga.<ref>[http://www.janes.com/security/international_security/news/sentinel/sent000904_6_n.shtml Jane's Sentinel examines the success of the LTTE in resisting the Sri Lankan forces]</ref> Government of India deputed Salim Ali IPS of CBI and [[Tirath Das Dogra|Professor T D Dogra]] of All India Institute of Medical Sciences to assist the investigations of Gamini Dissanayake's assassination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1994/Widow-Wants-Indian-Experts-To-Investigate-Assassination/id-a2700b4b6ccdb52a206b5f20f517c66f|title=WIDOW WANTS INDIAN EXPERTS TO INVESTIGATE ASSASSINATION|last=|first=|date=31 October 1994 <!-- 5:07 AM ET -->|website=|publisher=AP|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> His wife Srima Dissanayake ran in his stead, but was defeated by [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|People's Alliance]] candidate and Prime Minister [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]].\n\nHe has two sons, who are active in politics, Navin and Mayantha. His eldest son [[Navin Dissanayake|Navin]] was the Cabinet Minister of State Management Reforms in President [[Mahinda Rajapakse]]'s Government and Member of Parliament for [[Nuwara Eliya District]]; he was non-cabinet Minister of Investment Promotion too.  [[Mayantha Dissanayake|Mayantha]] contested for the [[2010 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2010 General Election]] for [[Kandy District]] as a UNP candidate.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of political families in Sri Lanka]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TKDg6TS_k4A Gamini Dissanayake Upahara '''''(One Hour Rare Video)''''']\n*[http://www.dailynews.lk/epaper/art.asp?id=2012/03/20/pg09_1&pt=p&h= A distinguished person and a noble son of Sri Lanka]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.island.lk/2008/10/23/features6.html  A Visionary Leader]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090228123355/http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/10/24/fea02.asp   A Charismatic and Caring Leader ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090322044434/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/03/20/fea02.asp Reflections on 67th Birth Anniversary ]\n*[http://www.dailynews.lk/epaper/art.asp?id=2012/10/23/pg09_0&pt=p&h= Gamini Dissanayake: Servant of Lanka]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.dailynews.lk/epaper/art.asp?id=2012/10/31/pg05_0&pt=p&h= QUALITIES OF Gamini Dissanayake]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://epaper.dailynews.lk/art.asp?id=2014/10/23/pg10_0&pt=p&h=  Gamini: The renaissance man]\n*[http://epaper.dailynews.lk/art.asp?id=2015/10/24/pg05_0&pt=p&h= Gamini Dissanayake, a political colossus]\n*[https://www.colombotelegraph.com/index.php/gamini-dissanayake-the-miracle-maker-the-robert-kennedy-of-sri-lanka/ The Miracle-Maker; The Robert Kennedy Of Sri Lanka]\n\n{{Sri Lankan Leaders of the Opposition}}\n{{Sri Lankan Irrigation and Water Resources Management ministers}}\n{{Sri Lankan Power & Energy ministers}}\n{{Members of 7th Parliament of Ceylon}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Kandy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dissanayake, Gamini}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Sri Lankan lawyers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sri Lanka Law College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Kandy]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Sri Lankan politicians]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (Sri Lanka)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th Parliament of Ceylon]]\n[[Category:Members of the 8th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:People killed during the Sri Lankan Civil War]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Kandy]]\n[[Category:Power ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Provincial councillors of Sri Lanka]] <!-- Ref: He was opposition leader of Central Provincial Council in 1993 -->\n[[Category:Sinhalese lawyers]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan cricket administrators]]\n[[Category:Suicide bombings in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Sri Lanka in 1994]]\n[[Category:United National Party politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Sri Lankan cricket umpire|Gamini Dissanayake (umpire)}}\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2015}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix  = [[The Honourable|Hon.]] \n| name              = Gamini Dissanayake\n| honorific-suffix  = \n| image             = Gamini Dissanayake.jpg\n| imagesize         = 250px\n| caption           = \n| office            = 10th [[Leader of the Opposition (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n| president         = [[Dingiri Banda Wijetunga]] \n| primeminister     = [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]]\n| predecessor       = [[Sirimavo Bandaranaike]]\n| successor         = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start        = 25 August 1994 \n| term_end          = 24 October 1994\n| office1           = Minister of Mahaweli Development\n| president1        = [[J.R Jayawardena]] [[Ranasinghe Premadasa]]\n| primeminister1 =[[Ranasinghe Premadasa]]  [[Dingiri Banda Wijetunga]]\n| term_start1 = 1977\n| term_end1   = 1990\n| nationality       = Sri Lankan\n| constituency_MP3  = [[Nuwara Eliya-Maskeliya Electoral District|Nuwara Eliya-Maskeliya]]\n| parliament3       = Sri Lankan\n| predecessor3      = ''Constituency Established''\n| successor3        = ''Constituency Abolished''\n| term_start3       = 1977\n| term_end3         = 1988\n| constituency_MP4  = [[Nuwara Eliya Electoral District (1947\u20131989)|Nuwara Eliya]]\n| parliament4       = Sri Lankan\n| predecessor4      = [[D.J. Ranaweera]]\n| successor4        = ''Constituency Abolished''\n| term_start4       = 1970\n| term_end4         = 1977\n| constituency_MP2  = [[Nuwara Eliya Electoral District]]\n| parliament2       = Sri Lankan\n| majority2         = 73,790 Preferential Votes \n| predecessor2      = \n| successor2        = \n| term_start2       = 1989\n| term_end2         = 1994\n| birth_name        = \n| birth_date        = 20 March 1942\n| birth_place       = Kandy, Sri Lanka\n| religion          = [[Theravada Buddhism|Buddhist]]\n| death_date        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1994|10|24|1942|03|20}}\n| death_place       = Colombo, Sri Lanka (assassinated)\n| profession        = Lawyer\n| occupation        = Politician\n| years_active      = 1970\u20131994\n| alma_mater        = [[Trinity College, Kandy]],<br /> [[Cambridge University|Cambridge University, UK]] \n| spouse            = [[Shrima Dissanayake]]\n| children          = [[Navin Dissanayake|Navin]], [[Mayantha Dissanayake|Mayantha]], Varuni.\n| website           =              \n}}\n'''Dissanayake Mudiyanse Ralahamilage Lionel Gamini Dissanayake''' (known as '''Gamini Dissanayake'''; {{lang-si|\u0dbd\u0dba\u0db1\u0dbd\u0dca \u0d9c\u0dcf\u0db8\u0dd2\u0dab\u0dd2 \u0daf\u0dd2\u0dc3\u0dcf\u0db1\u0dcf\u0dba\u0d9a}},{{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bbf \u0ba4\u0bbf\u0bb8\u0bbe\u0ba8\u0bbe\u0baf\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95}}; 20 March 1942 \u2013 24 October 1994) was a prominent Sri Lankan politician, a powerful minister of the [[United National Party]], and [[Leader of the Opposition (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the Opposition]]. He was designated as the UNP candidate in the [[1994 Sri Lankan presidential election|1994 presidential election]], but was then assassinated by the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE).\n\n==Early Life==\nHe was born in [[Kandy]] as the eldest son of a family of seven children to [[Andrew Dissanayake]] who served as an MP and a deputy minister in the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] government of [[Solomon Bandaranaike|S.W.R.D. Bandaranaike]]. His mother, Welegedara Samaratunga Kumarihamy of Kotmale. Born and bred in Kotmale, his basic values were cultivated in this rural milieu social surrounding and environment. The wealthy Dissanayake family resided in both [[Kandy]] as well as [[Nuwara Eliya]]. Dissanayake had his schooling at the prestigious [[Trinity College (Kandy)|Trinity College]] in Kandy, and received his tertiary education at the [[Sri Lanka Law College]]. Later in life, he completed an MPhil Degree in International Relations at [[Cambridge University]] UK.\n<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[File:Gamini Dissanayake statue.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Gamini Dissanayake statue at<br /> Viharamahadevi Park in Colombo]] -->\n\n==Political career==\nGamini Dissanayake won the 1970 elections and became a member of parliament under UNP candidature and was among one of the 18 UNP members in the parliament at a time when his party has faced an humiliating defeat. He comfortably secured his Nuwaraeliya-Maskeliya multielectorate seat in the 1977 elections and was appointed as the minister of Mahaweli Development. Dissanyake spearheaded the [[Mahaweli Development programme|Mahaweli Development Project]]. This was a huge project which was expected to take 30 years to finish. But due to Dissanayake's skills he managed to finish the project within 6 years. The Mahaweli Development Project is the largest development project conducted in Sri Lanka after independence. The whole country was affected by the project which focused on irrigation, hydro power generation, agriculture, town & country development. Further it was criticised by the time as to introduce sinhala population into Tamil's motherland. Majority of the power generated for the local consumption is generated from these hydropower plants while an overwhelming majority of the rice cultivation in Sri Lanka is conducted in these [[Mahaweli]] areas.\n\nHe was the chairperson of the Sri Lanka Cricket Board in the early 1980s and helped his country to gain the Test Status in cricket. He played a pivotal role in signing the Indoo-Lanka Peace Accord in 1987. In 1989 he was re elected as a MP from Nuwaraeliya District securing the highest percentage of preferential votes obtained by any UNP MP. He was the Minister of Estate Development during Premadasa regime. He was not awarded a portfolio in 1990 cabinet reshuffle and remained as a back-seat MP in the parliament. Dissanayake was accused of abduction of Prof. Ralph Bultjens. Prof Rohan Goonarathne in an interview with Hasitha Kuruppu told that Dissanayake did that as Bultjens in his lectures accused Dissanayake for swindling of money.<ref>GunaratnaRohan. Interview with Hasitha Kuruppu. Ceylontoday. November 2013</ref> Later he was acquitted from the courts.\n\nHe played a major role in the aborted impeachment motion against President Premadasa and as a result was expelled from UNP in 1992. In the same year Dissanayaka joined Lalith Athulathmudali to form United National Democratic Front (DUNF) which was a rising political force of that era. Dissanayaka contested to Kandy District at 1993 provincial council elections and became a member of the Central Provincial Council. After the assassination of Athulathmudali, Dissanayake became the leader of DUNF. Later he rejoined UNP and was appointed to the parliament as a national list MP and was offered a vital portfolio in the Wijethunga Government. In 1994 PA came to power defeating UNP when Dissanayaka was re elected as a member of parliament from Kandy District. In a contest held among UNP MPs to choose the opposition leader Dissanayaka recorded a comfortable victory over Ranil Wickramasinghe.\n\n==Assassination==\nWhen President [[Dingiri Banda Wijetunga|D.B. Wijetunga]] indicated he would not run in the [[1994 Sri Lankan presidential election|1994 presidential election]], Dissanayake was selected as the UNP candidate at the same time he was the Leader of the Opposition in parliament.  This was cut short when he was assassinated by a [[female suicide bomber]] of the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]] (LTTE) while he was addressing an election meeting at Thotalanga.<ref>[http://www.janes.com/security/international_security/news/sentinel/sent000904_6_n.shtml Jane's Sentinel examines the success of the LTTE in resisting the Sri Lankan forces]</ref> Government of India deputed Salim Ali IPS of CBI and [[Tirath Das Dogra|Professor T D Dogra]] of All India Institute of Medical Sciences to assist the investigations of Gamini Dissanayake's assassination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1994/Widow-Wants-Indian-Experts-To-Investigate-Assassination/id-a2700b4b6ccdb52a206b5f20f517c66f|title=WIDOW WANTS INDIAN EXPERTS TO INVESTIGATE ASSASSINATION|last=|first=|date=31 October 1994 <!-- 5:07 AM ET -->|website=|publisher=AP|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> His wife Srima Dissanayake ran in his stead, but was defeated by [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|People's Alliance]] candidate and Prime Minister [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]].\n\nHe has two sons, who are active in politics, Navin and Mayantha. His eldest son [[Navin Dissanayake|Navin]] was the Cabinet Minister of State Management Reforms in President [[Mahinda Rajapakse]]'s Government and Member of Parliament for [[Nuwara Eliya District]]; he was non-cabinet Minister of Investment Promotion too.  [[Mayantha Dissanayake|Mayantha]] contested for the [[2010 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2010 General Election]] for [[Kandy District]] as a UNP candidate.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of political families in Sri Lanka]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TKDg6TS_k4A Gamini Dissanayake Upahara '''''(One Hour Rare Video)''''']\n*[http://www.dailynews.lk/epaper/art.asp?id=2012/03/20/pg09_1&pt=p&h= A distinguished person and a noble son of Sri Lanka]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n*[http://www.island.lk/2008/10/23/features6.html  A Visionary Leader]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090228123355/http://www.dailynews.lk/2008/10/24/fea02.asp   A Charismatic and Caring Leader ]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090322044434/http://www.dailynews.lk/2009/03/20/fea02.asp Reflections on 67th Birth Anniversary ]\n*[http://www.dailynews.lk/epaper/art.asp?id=2012/10/23/pg09_0&pt=p&h= Gamini Dissanayake: Servant of Lanka]{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArch